+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_017AY3QQwpQHcPdo7o5Qjgck","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"As the reactive graph engine, I see something clearly: **don't separate parsing from dependency tracking**. When I parse a formula, I'm already discovering edges in the graph. The parser should naturally emit both an evaluable AST and the set of cell references it contains. And when evaluating, I should walk the AST and resolve references on the fly — no need for a separate \"compilation\" step. The simplicity is the power: parse → extract deps → check for cycles → evaluate in topological order → done.\n\nAlso: store formulas as raw strings but cache parsed ASTs. When a cell's value changes, I don't re-parse anything — I just re-evaluate the dependents in topological order. The parse only happens on `set()`."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":138,"cache_read_input_tokens":20743,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":138},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cfbc79c4-5107-4970-a054-4dc4348bc6b2","uuid":"1995dba9-3208-476b-ae50-5393b79a029b"}
